        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "from sklearn.datasets import load_iris\n",

        "\"\"\"\n",
        "KMeans Clustering Explanation:\n",
        "\n",
        "K-means clustering is an iterative algorithm that partitions data into K distinct clusters. The process works as follows:\n",
        "1. Initialize K centroids randomly in the feature space\n",
        "2. Assign each data point to the nearest centroid\n",
        "3. Update centroids by calculating the mean of all points assigned to each cluster\n",
        "4. Repeat steps 2-3 until convergence\n",
        "\n",
        "Why KMeans is suitable for the Iris dataset:\n",
        "1. The dataset has well-defined numerical features\n",
        "2. The data points form relatively compact clusters\n",
        "3. The features are on similar scales after standardization\n",
        "4. The dataset size is manageable for KMeans computation\n",
        "\"\"\""
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 7,
      "id": "03b44f86",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "03b44f86"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# Determine optimal number of clusters using elbow method\n",
        "inertias = []\n",
        "K = range(1, 11)\n",
        "for k in K:\n",
        "    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)\n",
        "    kmeans.fit(X_scaled)\n",
        "    inertias.append(kmeans.inertia_)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 8,
      "id": "f38b28d2",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 564
        },
        "id": "f38b28d2",
        "outputId": "781d8ef9-223a-4f80-9647-3de23ff35b63"
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "display_data",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": [
              "<Figure size 1000x600 with 1 Axes>"
            ],
            "image/png": "\n"
          },
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "# Plot elbow curve\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))\n",
        "plt.plot(K, inertias, 'bx-')\n",
        "plt.xlabel('k')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Inertia')\n",
        "plt.title('Elbow Method For Optimal k')\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 9,
      "id": "4c6fc41b",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "4c6fc41b"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# Apply KMeans clustering with optimal k=3\n",
        "kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=42)\n",
        "kmeans_labels = kmeans.fit_predict(X_scaled)"
      ]
    },

      "source": [
        "# Visualize KMeans clusters using first two features\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))\n",
        "scatter = plt.scatter(X_scaled.iloc[:, 0], X_scaled.iloc[:, 1],\n",
        "                     c=kmeans_labels, cmap='viridis')\n",

        "plt.title('KMeans Clustering Results')\n",
        "plt.colorbar(scatter)\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ]

      "source": [
        "\"\"\"\n",
        "Hierarchical Clustering Explanation:\n",
        "\n",
        "Hierarchical clustering creates a tree-like structure of clusters by either:\n",
        "1. Agglomerative (bottom-up): Start with individual points as clusters and merge similar clusters\n",
        "2. Divisive (top-down): Start with one cluster and recursively divide\n",
        "\n",
        "The algorithm works by:\n",
        "1. Computing distance between all pairs of points\n",
        "2. Merging the closest pairs into clusters\n",
        "3. Updating distances between new clusters\n",
        "4. Repeating until desired number of clusters is reached\n",
        "\n",
        "Why Hierarchical Clustering is suitable for the Iris dataset:\n",
        "1. Allows visualization of the clustering hierarchy through dendrograms\n",
        "2. No need to specify number of clusters beforehand\n",
        "3. Can reveal natural hierarchical structure in the data\n",
        "4. Works well with relatively small datasets like Iris\n",
        "\"\"\""
      ]
    },

        "# Create and plot dendrogram\n",

        "plt.ylabel('Distance')\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ]
